# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: slugging-percentage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:slugging-percentage/1958-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1958 Chicago White Sox season** was the team's 58th season in the major leagues, and its 59th season overall.
[src:slugging-percentage/1958-chicago-white-sox-season] They finished with a record of 82–72, good enough for second place in the American League, 10 games behind the first-place New York Yankees.
[src:slugging-percentage/1973-milwaukee-brewers-season] The **1973 Milwaukee Brewers season** was the 4th season for the Brewers in Milwaukee, and their 5th overall.
[src:slugging-percentage/1973-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers finished fifth in the American League East with a record of 74 wins and 88 losses.
[src:slugging-percentage/1973-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers' farm system consisted of four minor league affiliates in 1973.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] The **1980 Philadelphia Phillies season** was the team's 98th season in Major League Baseball (MLB) and culminated with the Phillies winning the World Series at home by defeating the Kansas City Royals in Game 6 on October 21, 1980.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] The team, after being swept by the Pirates four straight in Pittsburgh on August 8-10, won 36 of their final 55 games to finish with a regular-season record of 91 wins and 71 losses, which was good enough to win the National League East title by just one game over the division rival Montreal Expos.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] The Phillies went on to defeat the Houston Astros in the NLCS to gain their first NL title since 1950, and then defeated the Kansas City Royals to win their first World Series championship.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] The 1980 Phillies became the first team in the divisional era (since 1969) to win the World Series despite having the worst record of all teams in the postseason.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] The 1980 Phillies were known as "The Cardiac Kids" because of the many close games.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] Beginning that year, following the lead of the Yankees of the AL, the Phillies joined cable station PRISM with game broadcasts on that station.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p01] The Phillies won the National League East on the second-to-last day of the season with a 6–4 victory over the Expos in a game played in Montreal on October 4, 1980.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] When the modern-day World Series began in 1903, the National and American Leagues each had eight teams.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] With their victory in the 1980 World Series, the Phillies became the last of the "Original Sixteen" franchises to win a Series.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] The 1980 World Series was the first World Series to be played entirely on artificial turf.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Prior to 1980, the Phillies hadn't won a World Series game since Game 1 of the 1915 World Series against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] The series offered many intriguing storylines.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Phillies pitcher Bob Walk became the first rookie to start the first game of a World Series since Joe Black of the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1952.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] The 1980 World Series was the first of numerous World Series that journeyman outfielder Lonnie Smith (then with the Phillies) participated in.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] He was also a part of the 1982 World Series (as a member of the St.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Louis Cardinals), 1985 World Series (as a member of the Kansas City Royals), and the 1991 and 1992 World Series as a member of the Atlanta Braves.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Game 6 would be the culmination for the Phillies' first championship.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Philadelphia scored two in the third on a Mike Schmidt single.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] It was all that Steve Carlton and Tug McGraw would need for the 4–1 win.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Kansas City threatened by loading the bases in the eighth and the ninth innings before Tug McGraw struck out Willie Wilson for the third out in the final inning.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] While Mike Schmidt was the official MVP of the 1980 World Series, the Babe Ruth Award (another World Series MVP) was given to Tug McGraw.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] As of 2019, this is the last World Series in which both participating franchises had yet to win a World Series in their history.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] This was the first time that had happened since 1920.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] The entire state of Pennsylvania, not just Philadelphia, celebrated the Phillies' win.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] In 1980, Mike Schmidt won the National League's Most Valuable Player Award in a unanimous vote.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] He led the league in home runs with 48 (by a margin of 13 over his nearest competitor).
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Schmidt was also selected as MVP of the World Series, after hitting two homers and driving in seven runs as his team won their first World Series Championship over the George Brett-led Kansas City Royals.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Steve Carlton received the National League Cy Young Award.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Tug McGraw received the Babe Ruth Award.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] Manny Trillo was honored as the MVP of the National League Championship Series.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] In the National Hockey League, the Philadelphia Flyers reached the Stanley Cup Finals in May 1980 before losing four games to two to the New York Islanders.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] In the National Basketball Association also in May 1980, the Philadelphia 76ers reached the NBA Finals before losing four games to two to the Los Angeles Lakers.
[src:slugging-percentage/1980-philadelphia-phillies-season-p02] The 1980 Philadelphia Eagles would qualify for Super Bowl XV, where they were defeated 27–10 by the Oakland Raiders.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] The **2000 New York Mets season** was the 39th regular season for the Mets.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] They entered the season as defending National League runner ups, losing to the Atlanta Braves in the NLCS.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] They went 94–68 and finished second in the National League East, but earned the NL Wild Card.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] They made it to the World Series where they were defeated by their crosstown rival the New York Yankees.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] The Mets played in the first game held outside of North America on Opening Day, March 29.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] The Mets played the Chicago Cubs in front of over 55,000 at the Tokyo Dome in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:slugging-percentage/2000-new-york-mets-season] The Cubs won the game by a score of 5–3.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Where ERA is the pitcher's ERA, lgERA is the average ERA of the league, and PF is the park factor of the pitcher in question.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] The average ERA+ is set to be 100; a score above 100 indicates that the pitcher performed better than average, while below 100 indicates worse than average.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] For instance, imagine the average ERA in the league is 4.00: if pitcher A has an ERA of 4.00 but is pitching in a ballpark that favors hitters, his ERA+ will be over 100.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Likewise, if pitcher B has an ERA of 4.00 but pitches in a ballpark favoring pitchers, then his ERA+ will be below 100.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] As a result, ERA+ can be used to compare pitchers across different run environments.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] In the above example, while ERA will lead one to believe that both pitchers pitched at the same level due to their ERAs being equivalent, ERA+ indicates that pitcher A performed better than pitcher B.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] ERA+ can thus be used to neutralize the effects of some well-known advantages and disadvantages on pitchers' ERA scores.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Pedro Martínez holds the modern record for highest ERA+ in a single season; he posted a 1.74 ERA in the 2000 season while pitching in the American League, which had an average ERA of 4.92, which gave Martínez an ERA+ of 291.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] While Bob Gibson has the lowest ERA in modern times (1.12 in the National League in 1968), the average ERA was 2.99 that year (the so-called Year of the Pitcher) and so Gibson's ERA+ is 258, eighth highest since 1900.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] 1968 was the last year that Major League Baseball employed the use of a pitcher's mound at 15 inches (380 mm); after that season it was lowered to 10 inches (250 mm).
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] The career record for ERA+ (with a minimum of 1,000 innings pitched) is held by Mariano Rivera, a closer whose career ERA+ is 205.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Upon retirement in 2013, with an ERA+ of 194 in his final season, Rivera's career record of 205 surpassed the record among retired players of 154, held by Martínez, bumping Jim Devlin, a pitcher in the 1870s, to third with 151.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Roger Clemens topped a 200 ERA+ three times, and Greg Maddux had two such seasons.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Players in **bold** are active as of the end of the 2020 season and have not announced their retirement.
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Single-season leaders include only pitchers eligible for the ERA title (a pitcher must throw a minimum of one inning per game scheduled for his team during the season to qualify for the ERA title).
[src:slugging-percentage/adjusted-era] Only pitchers with 1,000 or more innings pitched are shown in the career leader list.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] Barra is a contributing editor of *American Heritage* magazine, and regularly writes about sports for *The Wall Street Journal* and *The Atlantic*.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] He has also written for *The New York Times* and *The New York Observer*, and was formerly a columnist for *Salon*.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] He formerly blogged on sports for the *Village Voice* website.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] He frequently contributes to Major League Baseball Radio and The Daily Beast.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] Barra, grew up in Birmingham, Alabama, currently lives in South Orange, New Jersey.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] Barra's book on Wyatt Earp has played a significant role in unwrapping the many fabricated biographies obscuring the real Earp.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] His 2009 book on Yogi Berra — *Yogi Berra: Eternal Yankee* — was praised as "sturdy," "well-written," and "thorough" by the *San Francisco Chronicle*, but *The New York Times* thought it too enthralled with its subject.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] In 2010, Barra wrote *Rickwood Field: A Century in America's Oldest Ballpark*.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] Barra was one of the few sportswriters to agree with Rush Limbaugh that Donovan McNabb had been overrated by sports journalists due to reasons related to McNabb's race.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] In 2009, he was the target of a widely read critique at the website *Deadspin*, which targeted Barra's subjective adoration for Derek Jeter.
[src:slugging-percentage/allen-barra] Jeter," rather than giving credit to the achievements of the team as a whole (six other members of the starting lineup had an OPS over 120+).
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:slugging-percentage/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] In baseball statistics, **slugging percentage** (**SLG**) is a measure of the batting productivity of a hitter.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Unlike batting average, slugging percentage gives more weight to extra-base hits such as doubles and home runs, relative to singles.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Batters who excel at getting extra-base hits are sometimes referred to as **sluggers**.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Plate appearances resulting in walks, hit-by-pitches, catcher's interference, and sacrifice bunts or flies are specifically excluded from this calculation, as such an appearance is not counted as an at-bat (these are not factored into batting average either).
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] The name is a misnomer, as the statistic is not a percentage but an average of how many bases a player achieves per at bat.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] It is a scale of measure whose computed value is a number from 0 to 4.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] A Major League Baseball player's slugging percentage is almost always less than 1.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] The stat awards a double twice the value of a single, a triple three times the value, and a home run four times.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] The slugging percentage would have to be divided by 4 to actually be a percentage (of bases achieved per at bat out of total bases possible).
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] As a result, it is occasionally called **slugging average**, or simply **slugging**, instead.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] A slugging percentage is usually expressed as a decimal to three decimal places and is generally spoken as if multiplied by 1000.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] For example, a slugging percentage of .589 would be spoken as "five eighty-nine." The slugging percentage can also be applied as an evaluative tool for pitchers.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] This is not as common but is referred to as "slugging-percentage against".
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] As an example: with the New York Yankees in 1920, Babe Ruth had 458 at bats during which he recorded 172 hits: 73 singles, 36 doubles, 9 triples, and 54 home runs.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] His total number of bases (388) divided by his total at-bats (458) is .847, which constitutes his slugging percentage for the season.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Ruth's 1920 figure set a record in Major League Baseball (MLB), which stood until 2001 when Barry Bonds achieved 411 bases in 476 at-bats for a slugging percentage of .863.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Josh Gibson, who played in Negro league baseball, had a slugging percentage of .974 in 1937.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Until the 2024 incorporation of Negro league statistics into major league records, the MLB career leader in slugging percentage was Ruth (.6897), followed by Ted Williams (.6338) and Lou Gehrig (.6324).
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Ruth was displaced by Josh Gibson, who has a career slugging percentage of .718.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] The maximum possible slugging percentage is 4.000.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] A number of MLB players have had a 4.000 career slugging percentage for a short amount of time by hitting a home run in their first major league at bat.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] However, no player in MLB history has ever retired with a 4.000 slugging percentage.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Four players have tripled in their only MLB plate appearance and therefore share the record—without consideration of a minimum number of games played or plate appearances—of a career slugging percentage of 3.000.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] They are Eric Cammack (2000 Mets); Scott Munninghoff (1980 Phillies); Eduardo Rodríguez (1973 Brewers); and Chuck Lindstrom (1958 White Sox).
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] For the 2023 season, the average slugging percentage for all players in MLB was .414.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] The highest single-season league average was .437 in 2000, and the lowest was .305 in 1908.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] A predecessor metric was developed by Branch Rickey in 1954.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Rickey, in *Life* magazine, suggested that combining OBP with what he called "extra base power" (EBP) would give a better indicator of player performance than typical Triple Crown stats.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] EBP was a predecessor to slugging percentage.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Allen Barra and George Ignatin were early adopters in combining the two modern-day statistics, multiplying them together to form what is now known as "SLOB" (Slugging × On-Base).
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] In 1984, Pete Palmer and John Thorn developed perhaps the most widespread means of combining slugging and on-base percentage: on-base plus slugging (OPS), which is a simple addition of the two values.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] Because it is easy to calculate, OPS has been used with increased frequency in recent years as a shorthand form to evaluate contributions as a batter.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] In a 2015 article, Bryan Grosnick made the point that "on base" and "slugging" may not be comparable enough to be simply added together.
[src:slugging-percentage/slugging-percentage] "On base" has a theoretical maximum of 1.000 whereas "slugging" has a theoretical maximum of 4.000.
